# Roadmap to 9.5/10: From MVP to World-Class

> **Current State**: 6.1/10 (Solo MVP with deep tech but significant risks)  
> **Target State**: 9.5/10 (Production-grade, scalable, secure, venture-backable)

To reach a **9.5/10** score, CGraph must transition from an "impressive solo prototype" to a "validated, scalable, and secure platform." This requires a shift in mindset: **prove it, don't just claim it.**

---

## Phase 1: Cleaning House (Months 1-2)

**Goal**: Eliminate debts that scream "amateur project" to investors/auditors.

### 1.1 Architecture Refactoring (The "God-Module" Fix)

- **Action**: Adopt **[CGraph Engineering Standards](./ENGINEERING_STANDARDS.md)** immediately. All new code MUST follow these rules.
- We must break the dangerously large files.
- **Action**: Refactor [forums.ex](file:///CGraph/apps/backend/lib/cgraph/forums.ex) (3,139 lines) into contexts:
  - `CGraph.Forums.Content` (Posts, Threads)
  - `CGraph.Forums.Moderation` (Mod actions, Queues)
  - `CGraph.Forums.Interaction` (Voting, Saving)
- **Action**: Split [gamification.ex](file:///CGraph/apps/backend/lib/cgraph/gamification.ex) and [messaging.ex](file:///CGraph/apps/backend/lib/cgraph/messaging.ex) similarly.
- **Why**: Keeps code maintainable and testable; critical for growing a team.

### 1.2 Security Hygiene

- **Action**: Fix `is_encrypted: false` default on messages to `true`.
- **Action**: Encrypt/Hash `recovery_codes` in the database immediately.
- **Action**: Remove [erl_crash.dump](file:///CGraph/apps/backend/erl_crash.dump) (10MB) and `monitoring_log` from git history.
- **Action**: Enable `validate_compile_env` in [mix.exs](file:///CGraph/apps/backend/mix.exs) for production safety.

### 1.3 Honest Documentation

- **Action**: Rewrite [CURRENT_STATE_DASHBOARD.md](file:///CGraph/docs/CURRENT_STATE_DASHBOARD.md) to reflect reality.
- **Action**: Delete the AI-generated 8,000-line [CODE_SIMPLIFICATION_GUIDELINES.md](file:///CGraph/docs/CODE_SIMPLIFICATION_GUIDELINES.md).
- **Why**: Transparency builds trust. Investors will respect a brutally honest "Work in Progress" more than a fake "10/10".

---

## Phase 2: Proving Scalability & Performance (Months 2-3)

**Goal**: Move from "theoretical" scalability to "proven" capabilities.

### 2.1 Message Storage Strategy

- **The "Hidden Cost" of ScyllaDB**: While the software is free, the _operational cost_ is massive.
  - **Infrastructure**: Minimum 3 nodes (CPU/RAM hungry) = ~$150-300/mo vs ~$20/mo for Postgres.
  - **Complexity**: Requires managing tokens, consistency levels, and repairs.
  - **Dev Time**: 2-3 weeks to rewrite the data access layer.
- **Strategic Decision**: Stick with **Partitioned PostgreSQL** until you hit **1M messages/day**.
  - **Action**: Implement the **Repository Pattern** now. This acts as an "interface" between your code and the database.
  - **Benefit**: This makes the future migration to ScyllaDB a code refactor, not a rewrite. You get 90% of the benefit (clean architecture) with 10% of the cost.
- **Action**: If staying on Postgres, implement **Read Replicas** configuration in `runtime.exs` and Fly.io config.

### 2.2 Load Testing

- **Action**: Run a real load test with **k6** or **Vegeta**.
  - Target: 10,000 concurrent WebSocket connections.
  - Target: 1,000 messages/sec throughput.
- **Action**: Publish the results in `docs/LOAD_TEST_RESULTS.md`.
  - Graphs of latency vs throughput.
  - CPU/Memory usage logs.

---

## Phase 3: Security Maturity (Months 3-4)

**Goal**: Transform "unaudited E2EE" redundancy into a verified asset.

### 3.1 External Audit

- **Action**: Commission a **formal security assessment** of the E2EE implementation (`@cgraph/crypto`).
  - Since funds might be tight, start with a "white box" review by a reputable freelance security researcher if a firm is too expensive.
- **Action**: Publish a transparent transparency report or security summary.

### 3.2 Advanced Security Features

- **Action**: Implement **Certificate Pinning** for mobile.
- **Action**: Add **Device Management** (view/revoke sessions) in the mobile app UI.

---

## Phase 4: Mobile & Frontend Robustness (Months 4-5)

**Goal**: Bring client-side coverage up to reliable standards.

### 4.1 Testing

- **Action**: Increase Mobile test coverage from 2.4% to **40%+**.
  - Focus: E2EE message flows, Auth flows, Push notification handling.
- **Action**: Increase Web test coverage from 7% to **50%+**.
- **Action**: Implement "Smoke Tests" that run on every PR (e.g., "Can a user log in and send a message?").

### 4.2 Error Handling

- **Action**: Implement proper **Error Boundaries** in React/React Native.
- **Action**: Ensure offline-first capabilities are robust (queueing messages when offline).

---

## Phase 5: The "9.5/10" Differentiator (Validation)

**Goal**: User validation. A 10/10 tech stack with 0 users is an academic exercise.

### 5.1 User Traction

- **Action**: Launch a **Closed Beta** (100-500 users).
- **Metric**: Achieve >40% D30 retention.
- **Why**: Real users break things in ways you cannot imagine. Fixing those bugs is what creates "Discord-grade" maturity.

### 5.2 Team Growth

- **Action**: Onboard **one** other contributor (even part-time/contract).
- **Why**: Proves the codebase is understandable by someone other than you (Bus Factor > 1).

---

## Scorecard Progression

| Quarter | Milestone                                             | Projected Score |
| ------- | ----------------------------------------------------- | --------------- |
| **Now** | Solo MVP, inflated docs, untested E2EE                | **6.1/10**      |
| **Q2**  | Clean architecture, honest docs, >40% test coverage   | **7.5/10**      |
| **Q3**  | Proven load tests, ScyllaDB plan, Security Audit      | **8.5/10**      |
| **Q4**  | 1,000 users, 2 contributors, production battle-tested | **9.5/10**      |
